Java/DOM is a terribly low-level tool for this job. XSLT has a bit of a learning curve but it ends up being far less code. Here&#39;s the solution in XSLT 3.0 (the hardest part was getting the blank lines in the right place):

    &lt;xsl:stylesheet xmlns:xsl=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform&quot; version=&quot;3.0&quot; expand-text=&quot;yes&quot;&gt;
        &lt;xsl:strip-space elements=&quot;*&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;xsl:output method=&quot;text&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;xsl:template match=&quot;REPORT_SUMMARY/CHARGE_SUMMARY&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:text&gt;CHARGE SUMMARY amount={@amount} date={@date} name={@name}&amp;#xa;&lt;/xsl:text&gt;      
        &lt;/xsl:template&gt;
        &lt;xsl:template match=&quot;RESOURCE&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:text&gt;&amp;#xa;&lt;/xsl:text&gt;
            &lt;xsl:apply-templates/&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:template&gt;
        &lt;xsl:template match=&quot;RESOURCE/CHARGE/VALUE&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:text&gt;RESOURCE name={../../@name} CHARGE name={../@name} VALUE amount={@amount} datetime={@datetime}&amp;#xa;&lt;/xsl:text&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:template&gt;
    &lt;/xsl:stylesheet&gt;

You can run this by installing Saxon-HE from SourceForge and either running it direct from the command line:

    java -jar saxon9he.jar -s:input.xml -xsl:stylesheet.xsl

or you can use the API to run it from your Java application.

How it works: the processor starts at the root node looking for a matching template rule. If there isn&#39;t one, it goes down a level, and so on recursively. There are three template rules here: one fires when you hit a CHARGE_SUMMARY, one when you hit a VALUE, and these just output the content in a fairly obvious way. The match=&quot;RESOURCE&quot; template is there only to output the blank lines between adjacent resources; it outputs a newline (`&amp;#xa;` in XML) and then calls xsl:apply-templates which means &quot;now process the next level down, using the appropriate template rules&quot;.

